<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1004,1319]" pageId="4" pageNumber="571">
This species was described from four females and two males taken from the flowers of 
<taxonomicName box="[1122,1310,1004,1030]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Meliaceae" genus="Melia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sapindales" pageId="4" pageNumber="571" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="azedarach">
<emphasis box="[1122,1310,1004,1030]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="571">Melia azedarach</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<date box="[1323,1432,1004,1031]" pageId="4" pageNumber="571" value="1915-01-14">14.i.1915</date>
, at Ibadan, 
<collectingCountry box="[274,361,1040,1066]" name="Nigeria" pageId="4" pageNumber="571">Nigeria</collectingCountry>
, but it has subsequently been identified from Sierre Leone, 
<collectingCountry box="[1057,1177,1040,1066]" name="Cameroon" pageId="4" pageNumber="571">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1190,1280,1040,1066]" name="Uganda" pageId="4" pageNumber="571">Uganda</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1294,1386,1040,1066]" name="Rwanda" pageId="4" pageNumber="571">Rwanda</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[151,237,1076,1102]" name="Angola" pageId="4" pageNumber="571">Angola</collectingCountry>
. It shares with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moulton" authorityYear="1940" box="[405,534,1076,1102]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Taeniothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="571" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fasciatus">
<emphasis box="[405,534,1076,1102]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="571">L. fasciatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the dark band at the apex of the fore wing, but the tergites of females have a distinctive colour pattern, with tergites VI–X brown, but the posterior half of VIII and the anterior third of IX sharply pale (
<figureCitation box="[215,300,1148,1174]" captionStart="FIGURES 17–23" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,453,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-157@6.[152,1436,453,1933]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 17–23. Lefroyothrips species. Female tergites VII–X, 17–19: (17) lefroyi; (18) pictus; (19) tribulationi. male tergite IX, 20–21: (20) pictus; (21) fasciatus. (22) lefroyi female sternites VI–VII. (23) fasciatus fore wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4543161" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4543161/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="571">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
). Antennal segments III–V (
<figureCitation box="[625,694,1148,1174]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1932,1956]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,417,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-137@3.[151,1435,417,1909]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Lefroyothrips species. Antennal segments, 1–6: (1) fasciatus holotype; (2) fasciatus male; (3) lefroyi; (4) pictus paratype; (5) tribulationi; (6) varatharajani. 7–8 lefroyi: (7) female; (8) head &amp; pronotum. L. tribulationi, 9–10: (9) head; (10) pronotum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4543157" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4543157/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="571">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
) are slightly less slender than in 
<taxonomicName box="[1076,1180,1148,1174]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Physothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="571" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lefroyi">
<emphasis box="[1076,1180,1148,1174]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="571">L. lefroyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and without the small sub-basal swelling found in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moulton" authorityYear="1940" box="[467,596,1184,1210]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Taeniothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="571" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fasciatus">
<emphasis box="[467,596,1184,1210]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="571">L. fasciatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
